Moneybox

Target IP: 192.168.170.230

Scanning



Three TCP ports are open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP. From the scan above, it looks like FTP allows anonymous login. HTTP application also exist on port 80. I will start my enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed when we browse to port 80 on the target machine. The source-code of the HTML page does not give us any information. So I will run directory search.


From the scan above, it looks like a directory called /blogs is present.


Browsing to /blogs shows us the webpage above.


However, viewing the source-code of the webpage gives us another interesting information: S3cr3t-T3xt hidden directory.


Following the hidden directory above, we get the webpage above.


And again, the source code of the webpage gives us another hint: 3xtr4ctd4t4. It seems to be a key for some sort of data.

Port 21: FTP

Since the FTP application allows anonymous login, I used this to download the file called trytofind.jpg.


The image from the FTP is shown above. Running binwalk and exiftool did not show anything useful.


However, running steghide shows a file called data.txt is embedded inside the image. I used the key 3xtr4ctd4t4 to extract the data. This text file contains a username renu, and apparently their password is weak -- maybe we can bruteforce it? The only port left is the SSH now.

Port 22: SSH

And the attacker was correct as renu uses a weak password of 987654321. I used hydra to bruteforce their password. The command I entered is hydra -l renu -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ssh://192.168.170.230. Now I should be able to gain a foothold.

Exploitation


Now I have a foothold on the machine as renu.

Privilege Escalation


The .ssh is interesting. There is an SSH key. The .bash_history is also interesting because it contains commands entered by the attacker to move the SSH key.


I copied this SSH key to my local machine, changed permission to 400, and logged in as lily with this key and it was successful.


Running sudo -l shows we can run /usr/bin/perl with root privileges.


And using sudo perl -e 'exec "/bin/sh";', I have a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt file once I gained a foothold on the machine as renu.


The proof.txt once I used perl to elevate my privileges to root.
